emic diseases such as HIV and tuberculosis also sculpt risk for human rights violations. He illustrates the ways that racism and gender inequality in the United States are embodied as disease and death. Yet this book is far from a hopeless inventory of abuse. Farmer’s disturbing examples are linked to a guarded optimism that new medical and social technologies will develop in tandem with a more informed sense of social justice. Otherwise, he concludes, we will be guilty of managing social inequality rather than addressing structural violence. Farmer’s urgent plea to think about human rights in the context of global public health and to consider critical issues of quality and access for the world’s poor should be of fundamental concern to a world characterized by the bizarre proximity of surfeit and suffering.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDiscrimination in medical care. 0aEquality. 0aHuman rights. 0aPoorxMedical care. 0aRight to health. 0aSocial stratification. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aactivism.  abiography memoir.  adisease.  adisturbing examples.  adoctor autobiography.  aepidemic.  ahaiti.  ahealth and wellness.  ahiv.  ahuman rights violations.  ahuman rights.  ahuman suffering.  ainequality.  aintegrity research board.  airb.  amedical advancement.  amedical anthropology.  amedical student.  amedical technology.  aoptimistic view.  apathologist.  apathology.  aperu.  aplague.  apolitical and economic injustice.  arussia.  asociology.  astories of illness.  astudy of disease.  astudying diseases.  atuberculosis.  aurgent plea.  aviolence.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024326240uhttps://doi.org/10.15